t5935.text: For macOS Word, it's under Format, then Font. The keyboard shortcut is Cmd + D. Of course, in LaTeX, these things are done automatically. Enjoy, and may you create more beautiful documents.

t5936.text: QUESTION: Where do I find these settings in Word? Please, let me show you. It's in the Home tab, in the Font group. Here are some screenshots from Windows Word 2016. (You can ignore "Stylistic sets" for the most part.)pic.twitter.com/jYonhHjvcY

t5937.text: Irrespective of whether you use old style or lining, proportional figures are best used when part of a running text. In tables, you'd want to use—tada!—tabular spacing. You want those decimal points and decimal place values bang-on aligned in tables.

t5938.text: In some instances, you might even prefer "old-style" number forms instead of "lining". By default, numbers in Word are set as lining—that is, all numbers are aligned the same, top and bottom. The last row shows old-style forms, where 3 dips below and 8 rises above, for example.pic.twitter.com/aGXF1oTJhs

t5939.text: Proportional number spacing is kind of like kerning. Typically, numbers have a fixed width, so 1 would have the same width as 0—ridiculous! The second one looks much nicer when surrounded by text.pic.twitter.com/wFX3gTCrkS

t5940.text: * Sometimes, ligatures create a separation between graphemes, such as "gg" and "gy" in some typefaces.

t5941.text: Ligatures are graphemes (letters) that are connected* to form one glyph. The second row here has ligatures turned on; the first does not. Notice how the dots of the i and j disappear, for example, and becomes the tip of f. Beautiful! pic.twitter.com/7KkAlYBibX

t5942.text: Of course, kerning can go wrong. When this occurs, it's called "keming" (bad kerning). Here's a good example for FINAL CLEARANCE. (Source: https://boingboing.net/2016/11/14/fine-examples-of-the-typograph.html ….)pic.twitter.com/m9rJ3mEl3d

t5943.text: Kerning is the process of adjusting the space between glyphs. In this image, note than the second and fourth rows take up less space because letters have been squished together (very obvious with LVAT). This is much more visually pleasing because excess white space disappears.pic.twitter.com/dkNKpVoLw0

t5944.text: The problem is that the default Word settings make the typeface—any OpenType typeface, really—less beautiful than it actually is. These settings have to do with kerning, ligatures, and spacing. Let's talk about them in turn.

t5945.text: One quick historical note, though: "Times" comes from the Times of London, a newspaper, which commissioned Monotype (a font foundry) to create a new font. This explains why the typeface is relatively narrow: the publisher wanted to maximize the use of newspaper real estate.

t5946.text: The main issue, as my man @mbutterick puts it, is that "Times New Roman is not a font choice so much as the absence of a font choice, like the blackness of deep space is not a color." Fair! But Calibri is now the default in Word, so *choosing* Times New Roman *is* a statement.

t5947.text: Since #TimesNewRoman is trending today, I thought I might talk about it a little. It's unfortunately much maligned, but it's actually a rather good typeface—but you can make it even better! In this thread, I'll show you how (in Word).
